00:44:32.140 --> 00:44:34.120
But yes, it's an
interesting question.

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:37.320
And we've talked about studying
the bacteria from the soil you

00:44:37.320 --> 00:44:41.010
just outside the bone and inside
the bone, and comparing that

00:44:41.010 --> 00:44:43.880
and see if one can
fish out something

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:47.410
AUDIENCE: So since the
DNA or the bone fragments

00:44:47.410 --> 00:44:49.750
were found in Europe,
how do you know

00:44:49.750 --> 00:44:54.844
that the contamination is
not from European humans?

00:44:54.844 --> 00:44:56.010
How do you control for that?

00:44:56.010 --> 00:45:00.692
SVANTE PAABO: That add
mixture signal, yes.

00:45:00.692 --> 00:45:04.330
So I mean, there are
a lot more analysis

00:45:04.330 --> 00:45:09.880
than what I present here
that really indicate that.

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:14.460
For example, if you look
in the present-day humans,

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:18.000
in the fragments
that are particularly

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:22.836
close to the Neanderthal,
say, in an individual, in me,

00:45:22.836 --> 00:45:25.230
those fragments are
also particularly

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:28.040
different from everyone
else in Europe.

00:45:28.040 --> 00:45:30.840
So if you just
plot, say, fragments

00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:34.790
where I'm closer and closer
to Neanderthal, most of that

00:45:34.790 --> 00:45:36.740
is simply due to that
these are regions

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:38.560
of the genome that
change slowly.

00:45:38.560 --> 00:45:41.211
But then I also get closer
and closer to other Europeans

00:45:41.211 --> 00:45:41.710
today.

00:45:41.710 --> 00:45:44.580
These are assay regions
that change slowly.

00:45:44.580 --> 00:45:47.260
But when I get really close
to the Neanderthal, then

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:50.010
suddenly I'm more different
from everyone else.

00:45:50.010 --> 00:45:52.290
So that's another
line of evidence

00:45:52.290 --> 00:45:56.104
to say that these are really
things from the Neanderthal.

